AIM

Automate the process of running the containerized application developed in Experiment-07 using Kubernetes.


Exp-09

OBJECTIVE

Automate building and deploying the application using Kubernetes

Manage container images using Docker

Apply Kubernetes Deployment and Service files

Integrate Jenkins + GitHub + Docker + Kubernetes


Exp-09

SOFTWARE REQUIREMENTS

Docker Desktop

Kubernetes (Minikube OR Docker Desktop Kubernetes)

kubectl CLI

GitHub Account

Jenkins

VS Code / Any Editor

Containerized application from Experiment-07


Exp-09

ðŸš€ STEP 1 â€” Clone the Repository

Clone the given GitHub repository:

git clone https://github.com/shiv4j/kube


Make sure the repo contains:

my-kube1-deployment.yaml

my-kube1-service.yaml

Push this repository to your own GitHub account (OR fork it directly).
After pushing, GitHub should show all the files like shown in the PDF (page 1).


Exp-09

ðŸš€ STEP 2 â€” Configure Jenkins with Your GitHub Repo

Open Jenkins Dashboard â†’ New Item

Enter a project name

Select Pipeline Project

Go to Pipeline tab

Set:

Definition: Pipeline script from SCM

SCM: Git

Repository URL: your GitHub repo URL

Branch: main / master (based on your repo)

Click Apply â†’ Save

The screenshot on PDF page 2 shows the Jenkins configuration exactly.


Exp-09

âž¤ Build the Jenkins Job

Click Build Now.

A green tick means the pipeline is successful (page 3 screenshot).


Exp-09

ðŸš€ STEP 3 â€” Push Docker Image to Docker Hub

After Jenkins build, a Docker image is created (shown on PDF page 4).


Exp-09

1. Login to Docker Hub:
docker login

2. Tag the generated image:
docker tag <local-image-name>:<tag> yourusername/image-name:<tag>


Example from PDF:

docker tag kube:latest rajshreel023/kube1:latest


Exp-09

3. Push image to Docker Hub:
docker push yourusername/image-name:<tag>


Example:

docker push rajshreel023/kube1:latest


The console output of a successful push is shown on PDF page 4.


Exp-09

ðŸš€ STEP 4 â€” Deploy Application Using Kubernetes
1. Start Kubernetes:

(If using Minikube)

minikube start


Exp-09

2. Apply Deployment file:
kubectl apply -f my-kube1-deployment.yaml

3. Apply Service file:
kubectl apply -f my-kube1-service.yaml


Exp-09

4. Check Deployment and Pods:
kubectl get pods
kubectl get service

5. Open Kubernetes Dashboard:
minikube dashboard


This opens the dashboard in default browser where you can see Pods, Services, Deployments (PDF page 6).
